The graph of $y = ax^2 + bx + c$ is reflected about the $x$-axis to become $y = -ax^2 - bx - c.$  Then the graphs of $y = ax^2 + bx + c$ and $y = -ax^2 - bx - c$ are translated horizontally 5 units in opposite directions to become the graphs of $y = f(x)$ and $y = g(x),$ respectively.

[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

real a = 0.5, b = -3, c = 5;
real f(real x) {
  return (a*(x - 5)^2 + b*(x - 5) + c);
}
real g(real x) {
  return (-a*(x + 5)^2 - b*(x + 5) - c);
}

draw(graph(f,-3,5),red);
draw(graph(g,-5,3),blue);
draw((-3,-10)--(5,-10),dashed);
draw((3,-10)--(3,10));
draw((5,-10)--(5,10));

label("$y = f(x)$", (5,f(5)), E, red);
label("$y = g(x)$", (-5,g(-5)), W, blue);
label("$y = f(x) + g(x)$", (5,f(5) + g(5)), E);
[/asy]

Then
\[y = f(x) + g(x) = ax^2 + bx + c - ax^2 - bx - c = 0.\]Thus, the graph of $y = (f + g)(x)$ is the $\boxed{\text{(C)}}$ the horizontal line $y = 0.$
